{
  "verdict": "vulnerable",
  "confidence": 0.93,
  "vulnerabilities": [
    {
      "type": "Missing access control on resource registration enables unbacked deposits (fake ERC20) and downstream mint/inflation",
      "severity": "critical",
      "vulnerable_lines": [61, 62, 63, 64, 57, 58],
      "location": "BridgeHandler.setResource() / BridgeHandler.deposit()",
      "explanation": "BridgeHandler.setResource() is permissionless, so any attacker can map any resourceID to any token contract address (including a malicious ERC20). BridgeHandler.deposit() then trusts IERC20(token).transferFrom(...) solely by checking the returned boolean. A malicious token can return true without transferring any tokens. As a result, CrossChainBridge.deposit() will emit a Deposit event for a deposit that is not actually backed by locked assets. In typical bridge architectures, relayers/watchers act on this event to mint/release assets on the destination chain, so this becomes a direct unbacked mint/inflation vector without requiring any trusted role compromise.",
      "attack_scenario": "1) Attacker deploys a malicious ERC20 contract where transferFrom(...) always returns true and does not transfer tokens (and may ignore allowances).\n2) Attacker calls BridgeHandler.setResource(resourceID, maliciousTokenAddress) for a resourceID that relayers/bridge UI will accept (or any resourceID if relayers mint based on event content).\n3) Attacker calls CrossChainBridge.deposit(destinationDomainID, resourceID, abi.encode(largeAmount)).\n4) BridgeHandler.deposit() calls maliciousToken.transferFrom(...), which returns true; the handler believes tokens were locked.\n5) CrossChainBridge emits Deposit event; relayer mints/releases real assets on the destination chain to the attacker, despite no source-chain collateral being locked.",
      "suggested_fix": "1) Add strict access control to setResource(): onlyOwner / onlyAdmin / onlyRole(RESOURCE_ADMIN).\n2) Enforce token allowlisting in deposit() (use contractWhitelist properly) so only pre-approved token contracts can be used.\n3) Consider making BridgeHandler.deposit() callable only by the trusted CrossChainBridge contract (e.g., require(msg.sender == bridgeAddress)).\n4) For extra safety, verify actual balance change when locking tokens (pre/post balance) and use OpenZeppelin SafeERC20 to handle non-standard ERC20 behavior."
    }
  ],
  "overall_explanation": "The contract is critically vulnerable because anyone can register/overwrite resourceID -> token mappings, enabling deposits against malicious tokens that pretend to transfer funds. This can produce valid-looking Deposit events without locking collateral, which in a standard bridge flow allows unbacked minting/release on the destination chain. Fix by adding access control to resource registration, enforcing allowlists, restricting who can call deposit on the handler, and validating real token transfers."
}
